Description: Body fragment (mended from three sherds) of perhaps North Ionian pottery dinos (?); interior reserved; exterior: fugitive buff slip (?), black-brown, red and white paint; decoration of worn horizontal bands; inscription incised on the outside.
Excavator/field collector: Excavated by: Dr David George Hogarth
Findspot: Excavated/Findspot: Hellenion (Naukratis), Probably Site 57 (Hogarth) or Site 63 (Hogarth) (Hogarth notes the find of dedications to the 'gods of the Greeks' at Sites 57 and 63: Hogarth 1903, 115)
Curator's comments: Object owned and held by the Ashmolean Museum, Oxford. This record is included in the British Museum database as part of the Museum’s Naukratis Project, a research collaboration that aims to virtually re-unite finds from the ancient port city of Naukratis, now distributed over 80 museums worldwide.

Last letter of l. 2 unlikely to be rho; this would rule out any equation of the piece with that noted by C.A. Hutton in Classical Review 7 (1893) 83, II, which has not been located. Höckmann & Möller 2006 no. 22, with erroneous reading and date.
Bibliographic references: Bernand 1970 / Le Delta égyptien d'après les textes grecs, i: les confins libyques (p. 706, no. 644, pl. 25.8)
Villing et al 2013-2015 / Naukratis: Greeks in Egypt (GG.414)
Previous owner: Currently owned by: Ashmolean Museum, University of Oxford
